[Student "S"]
{When partner opens 1NT, interference can easily gum up your smooth bidding sequences. Playing the lebensohl convention, your 3\H bid shows a 5-card suit and is forcing to game.

It doesn't always work out so well, but here partner had an easy 4\H bid.

West plays 4\H. North leads the \ST.

Whatever you play, South takes the \S A K J and then plays a small \C. North started with just one \S.

Loser List: \S = 3 : \H = ? : \D = 0 : \C = 0 :: Total = ?

Don't let that Question Mark by the \H losers mislead you - if you are going to make this contract you cannot lose a \H trick at all! Is there any hope? 

The odds aren't good, but you actually have <b>TWO</b> possibilities for success. If North holds the singleton \HK, you can play a small \H to dummy's \HA, dropping the \HK, then finesse South out of his \HJ. Or, if South holds the singleton \HJ you can play your \HQ, finessing North for the \HK and at the same time smothering South's \HJ.

Which basket will you put your eggs into? 

The answer is simple Bridge math! South started with 6 \Ss leaving him 7 cards outside the \S suit. North started with just 1 \S, leaving him with 12 cards outside the \S suit. Obviously South is much more likely to have a singleton \H than North.

So you win the \CA in your hand, play the \HQ and let it ride if North does not cover.

Then you  

Ahh, success.

But to tell the truth, the Bridge math wasn't really complete. Distribution-wise it was just fine, but there is also the question of strength.

The fact that South overcalled makes it more likely that he holds more high cards than North, and this skews the odds toward South holding the \HK.

But think about it. If South does in fact hold the singleton \HK, and if you cleverly drop it by playing dummy's \HA it won't help you. You will then have to lose a trick to North's \HJ.}
[Play "W"]ST

